message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Among the options, only abnormal development of endocardial cushions will most likely result in atrioventricular septal defect. Sinus venosus defect is caused by a deficiency in the wall separating the systemic and pulmonary veins. Transposition of the great vessels is caused by transposition of the primary arteries during fetal development. Dextrocardia is a rare condition where the heart is situated on the right side of the chest rather than the left.
We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Abnormal development of the endocardial cushions is associated with atrioventricular septal defects.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Endocardial cushions are responsible for the formation of the atrial septum, ventricular septum, and AV valves. Abnormal development of the endocardial cushions is most likely to result in an atrioventricular septal defect (AVSD). Sinus venosus defect is caused by a defect in the superior vena cava or right atrium. Transposition of the great vessels is caused by an abnormal position of the aorta and pulmonary artery. Dextrocardia is a rare condition where the heart is located on the right side of the chest instead of the left.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Abnormal development of the endocardial cushions is most commonly associated with an atrioventricular septal defect. The other options are not typically associated with this type of cardiac defect.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Abnormal development of the endocardial cushions is most commonly associated with atrioventricular septal defects. Sinus venosus defects involve the superior vena cava, inferior vena cava, or both, while transposition of the great vessels involves a reversal of the aorta and pulmonary artery. Dextrocardia is a condition in which the heart is situated on the right side of the body rather than the left, and is not directly related to a cardiac defect resulting from abnormal endocardial cushion development.
